{"key":"processedPost-10716918","value":{"id":10716918,"first":10716691,"last":10717143,"when":1248223171,"utime":"07/22/09 03:39 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />The tek I was reading never mentioned this.&nbsp; It just used a casing. </blockquote><br />Coir is a bulk substrate material, just like manure or compost.&nbsp; The reason you're confused is because whomever wrote the tek was misusing terms.&nbsp; There's so many people using the wrong nomenclature around here, it confuses the new people, and then they have to un-learn all the bad info.<br />60/40 verm/coir was used as a 'casing' layer a quite a bit a few years ago, but in reality it was adding a top layer of bulk substrate, since mycelium derives food value from both the coir and the verm.&nbsp; Cubensis fruits just fine on an uncased bulk substrate.<br />Skip the calcium carbonate.&nbsp; You don't need a pH adjustment with bulk substrates.&nbsp; Use gypsum at about 5% or so by volume to the amount of coir.<br />You can either mix the spawn and bulk materials together, or layer them.&nbsp; I prefer to layer, but it's commonly done both ways.<br />RR","title":"Re: Rye, Casing, Gypsum, Coffee, and Calcium Carbonate?"}}